entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 23 at 3:15PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
A tropical disturbance, known as Invest 98W from the Joint Typhoon Warning Center, continues to slowly develop near Chuuk at 8.1N 151.2E. This system will slowly continue westward before turning towards the Marianas around Friday, gradually strengthening as it does so. Computer model guidance continues to highlight the potential for this developing system to pass through the Marianas.
POTENTIAL IMPACTS: - Sustained winds exceeding 30 mph.
- Locally heavy rainfall potentially causing flash flooding, especially in areas of poor drainage or in the valleys of hilly terrain.
- Hazardous surf and marine conditions.
As this disturbance is still poorly organized, uncertainty remains high regarding the timing of its eventual consolidation and turn to the northwest. Continue to monitor latest forecasts from weather.gov/gum and information from your local emergency management offices.

cap:parameter.value: DEVELOPING TROPICAL DISTURBANCE ANTICIPATED TO AFFECT THE REGION SOMETIME BETWEEN FRIDAY AND SUNDAY... ...RAIN AND WIND POTENTIAL DEPENDENT ON THE EVENTUAL MOTION

* WHAT...For the Coastal Flood Warning, significant coastal flooding. For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents.
* WHERE...Inland St. Johns, Inland Flagler, Eastern Clay, Eastern Putnam, Trout River and South Central Duval Counties.
* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Warning, until 6 AM EDT Wednesday. For the High Rip Current Risk, through late tonight.
* IMPACTS...Numerous roads may be closed. Low lying property including homes, businesses, and some critical infrastructure will be inundated. Some shoreline erosion will occur. Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away from shore into deeper water.

entry.title: Air Quality Alert issued October 21 at 3:43PM EDT by NWS Indianapolis IN
entry.summary:
The officials at the Indiana Department of Environmental Management have declared an Air Quality Action Day, IN EFFECT FROM 8 PM THIS EVENING TO 8 AM EDT TUESDAY.
An Air Quality Action Day for PM 2.5 has been issued. Fine particulate levels are expected to be in the Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups range. Active children and adults, and people with respiratory disease, such as asthma should limit prolonged outdoor exposure.
Here are some recommended actions that the public can take:
* Walk, bike, carpool or use public transportation. * Avoid using the drive-through and combine errands into one trip. * Avoid refueling your vehicle or using gasoline-powered lawn equipment until after 7pm. * Turn off your engine when idling for more than 30 seconds. * Conserve energy by turning off lights or setting the air conditioner to 75 degrees or above.
For additional information, please visit the IDEM Smog page at:
https://apps.idem.in.gov/smogwatch
